<section>
<title>Note:  index sets</title>

<p>When we have a collection of things, we often organize them using an <term>index</term>.  This is especially helpful when we need to order or manipulate elements of the collection.</p>

<example>
  <title>Finite sum</title>
  <p>Consider this finite collection of numbers <m>A=\{a_1, a_2,a_3,\ldots,a_N\}</m>.  Here we are using subscripts to index the numbers in this collection.  Let <m>I=\{1, 2, 3,\ldots,N\}</m>.  This is the index set we are using to index our collection of numbers.  We can use it to express <m>A</m> using the index set <m>I</m> as follows:
    <md>
      <mrow>A=\{a_i \, : \, i \in I\}.</mrow>
    </md></p>
  <p>When we learned about sigma-notation in Calculus 1, we learned to write the sum of the numbers in <m>A</m> as
      <md>
      <mrow>\displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^N a_i.</mrow>
    </md>
  In this notation we actually call <m>i</m> the <term>index of summation</term>.  We can write the same sum using the index set <m>I</m> as follows:
    <md>
      <mrow>\displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^N a_i =  \sum_{i \in I} a_i.</mrow>
    </md></p>
</example>


</section>
  
<!-- ========================================   -->

<section>
<title>Note:  index sets</title>


<example>
  <title>Series</title>
  <p>Consider the infinite collection of numbers <m>A=\{a_1, a_2,a_3,\ldots,\}</m>.  Here we are using subscripts to index the numbers in this collection, and the index set is <m>\mathbb{N}</m>.  We can use the index to express <m>A</m> as follows:
    <md>
      <mrow>A=\{a_i \, : \, i \in \mathbb{N}\}.</mrow>
    </md></p>
  <p>When we learned about sigma-notation in Calculus 1, we learned to write the infinite sum of the numbers in <m>A</m> as
      <md>
      <mrow>\displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^{\infty} a_i.</mrow>
    </md>
We can write the same sum using the index set <m>I</m> as follows:
    <md>
      <mrow>\displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^{\infty} a_i = \sum_{i \in \mathbb{N}} a_i.</mrow>
    </md></p>
</example>

<example>
  <title>Collections</title>
  <p>Suppose we have a mathematical object <m>X_{\lambda}</m>.  (This object cold be a number, or a set, or a function, or something else.). Here <m>\lambda</m> is going to serve as an index.  Let <m>\Lambda</m> be our index set.  Then the set (or collection) of all our objects can be written
    <md>
      <mrow>X = \{ x_{\lambda} \, : \, \lambda \in \Lambda\}.</mrow>
    </md></p>
  <p>If the objects are numbers, we could write their sum as
    <md>
      <mrow>\sum_{\lambda \in \Lambda} X_{\lambda}.</mrow>
    </md></p>
 <p>If the objects are sets, we could write their union as
    <md>
      <mrow>\displaystyle \bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} X_{\lambda}.</mrow>
    </md>
  and their intersection as 
    <md>
      <mrow>\displaystyle \bigcap_{\lambda \in \Lambda} X_{\lambda}.</mrow>
    </md></p>
    <p>And so on.</p>
</example>

</section>
  
<!-- ========================================   -->

<section>
<title>Compactness</title>

<definition>
  <statement>
    <p>A set <m>K \subset \mathbb{R}</m> is <term>(sequentially) compact</term> if every sequences in <m>K</m> has a subsequence that converges in <m>K</m>.</p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<example>
  <title><m>[0,1]</m> is compact</title>
  <p>Consider <m>K=[0,1] \subset \mathbb{R}</m>.  We want to show that <m>K</m> is compact.</p>
  <p>Let <m>(x_n) \subset K</m> be a sequence.  We will show that <m>(x_n)</m> has a subsequence <m>(x_{n_k})</m> that converges in <m>K</m>. That means <m>(x_{n_k}) \rightarrow x_0 \in K</m>. </p>
  <p>Since <m>0 &lt; x_n &lt; 1</m> for all <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>, the sequence <m>(x_n)</m> is bounded.  The Bolzano-Weierstrass Theorem tells us that <m>(x_n)</m> has a subsequence <m>(x_{n_k})</m> that converges in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.  Let<m>x_0</m> be the limit point of that subsequence.  Since <m>K</m> is closed, it contains all its limit points.  By Theorem 3.2.5, <m>x_0</m> is a limit point of <m>K</m>. Therefore, <m>x_0 \in K</m>.  This shows that <m>[0,1]</m> is compact.</p>
</example>

<example>
  <title><m>[a,b]</m> is compact</title>
  <p>For exact same reason, every closed and bonded interval is compact.</p>
</example>

<p>Recall that a set <m>A \subset \mathbb{R}</m> is <term>bounded</term> if there is an <m>M \in \mathbb{R}</m> for which <m>-M \leq x \leq M</m> for all <m>x \in A</m>.</p>

</section>
  
<!-- ========================================   -->

<section>
<title>Compactness</title>

<theorem>
    <statement>
      <p>A set<m>K \subset \mathbb{R}</m> is (sequentially) compact if and only if <m>K</m> is closed and bounded.</p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  <proof>
    <p>(<m>\Rightarrow</m>). Suppose<m>K</m> is compact.  We must show that <m>K</m> is closed and bounded.</p>
    <p>Suppose that <m>K</m> is not bounded.  Then for each <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m> there is an <m>x_n \in K</m> with <m>|x_n| &gt; n</m>.  These elements of <m>K</m> form a sequence <m>(x_n) \subset K</m>.  Since <m>K</m> is (sequentially) compact, the sequence has a subsequence <m>(x_{n_k})</m> that converges in <m>K</m>.  But <m>|x_{n_k}| &gt; n_k \rightarrow \infty</m> as <m>k \rightarrow \infty</m>.  This means that the subsequence is unbounded.  However, we've proved that convergent sequences must be bounded.  This is a contradiction.  Therefore, <m>K</m> must be bounded.</p>
    <p>To see that <m>K</m> is closed, let <m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m> be a limit point of <m>K</m>.  We must show that <m>x \in K</m>.  Since <m>x</m> is a limit point of <m>K </m>, there is a sequence <m>(y_k) \subset K</m> that converges to <m>x</m>.  Since <m>K</m> is (sequentially) compact, <m>(y_k)</m> has a subsequence <m>(y_{k_{\ell}})</m> that converges in <m>K</m>.  We know that a subsequence of a convergent sequence must converge to the same limit at the sequence, so <m>(y_{k_{\ell}}) \rightarrow x</m>, and <m>x \in K</m>.  This shows that<m>K</m> is closed.</p>
<p>This completes the proof in this direction.</p>
<p>(<m>\Leftarrow</m>). Suppose<m>K</m> is closed and bounded.  We must show <m>K</m> is compact.  Let <m>(x_n) \subset K</m> be a sequence.  We must show that <m>(x_n)</m> has a subsequence that converges to a point in <m>K</m>.</p>
<p>Because <m>K</m> is bounded, there is an <m>M \in \mathbb{R}</m> with <m>M &gt; 0</m> such that <m>|x| &lt; M</m> for all <m>x \in K</m>.  Therefore, <m>|x_n| &lt; M</m> for all <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>.  This means that <m>(x_n)</m> is a bonded sequence.  The Bolzao-Weierstrass Theorem implies that <m>(x_n)</m> has a convergent subsequence <m>(x_{n_k})</m>. Since <m>(x_{n_k}) \subset K</m> and <m>K</m> is closed (it contains all its limit points), <m>\displaystyle \lim_{k \rightarrow \infty} (x_{n_k}) \in K</m>.  This shows that that <m>K</m> is compact.</p>
<p>This completes the proof.</p>
  </proof> 

</section>
  
<!-- ========================================   -->

<section>
<title>Nested Set Property</title>

<theorem>
  <title>Nested Set Property</title>
  <statement>
    <p>If <m>K_i</m> is a nonempty (sequentially) compact set, and if <m>K_i \supseteq K_{i+1}</m> for all <m>i \in \mathbb{N}</m> then <m>\displaystyle \cap_{i=1}^{\infty} K_i</m> is nonempty.</p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

<p>This statement should look familiar.</p>

<p>This is a generalization of the Nested Interval Property that replaces intervals with compact sets.</p>

<proof>
  <p>For each <m>n \in\mathbb{N}</m>, because <m>K_n</m> is nonempty, we can find an element in <m>K_n</m>, call it <m>x_n</m>.  This creates a sequence <m>(x_n) \subset \mathbb{R}</m>.  Since <m>K_n \subseteq K_1</m> for all <m>n</m>, <m>(x_n) \subset K_1</m>.  Because <m>K_1</m> is a (sequentially) compact set, <m>(x_n) \subset K_1</m> has a subsequence <m>(x_{n_{\ell}}) \subset K_1</m> that converges in <m>K_1</m>.  Call its limit <m>x \in K_1</m>.</p>
  <p>Notice that, given any <m>m \in \mathbb{N}</m>, <m>K_m</m> contains the tail of <m>(x_n)</m>.  Specifically, <m>(x_n)_{n=m}^{\infty} \subset K_m</m>.  Since <m>K_m</m> is compact, the limit of <m>(x_n)</m> is in <m>K_m</m>, i.e., <m>x \in K_m</m>.  It follows that <m>\displaystyle x \in \bigcap_{m=1}^{\infty} K_m
  </m>.</p>
  <p>This completes the proof.</p>
</proof>
</section>
  
<!-- ========================================   -->

<section>
<title>Open Covers</title>

<p>Let <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>.  Let <m>U_i \subset \mathbb{R}</m> be open for <m>i \in I</m> where <m>I</m> is some index set.  We say the collection <m>\mathcal{U}=\{U_i \, : \, i \in I\}</m> is an <term>open cover</term> for <m>A</m> if
<md>
  <mrow>\displaystyle A \subseteq \bigcup_{i \in I} U_i</mrow>
</md>
If <m>I_0 \subseteq I</m> is a finite subset of the inde <m>I</m> for which 
<md>
  <mrow>\displaystyle A \subseteq \bigcup_{i \in I_0} U_i</mrow>
</md>
we call <m>\{I_i \, :\, i \in I_0\}</m> a <term>finite subcover</term> of <m>A</m>.
</p>

<p>A set <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> can have many possible open covers.  Here are some examples.</p>

<example>
  <title>An open cover of <m>[a,b]</m></title>
  <p workspace="2in">Consider the set <m>U=(a-1,b+1)</m>.  The collection <m>\mathcal{U}=\{U\}</m> is an open over because
    <md>
      <mrow>\displaystyle \bigcup_{U \in \mathcal{U}} U \amp = U =(a-1,b+1) \supset [a,b].</mrow>
    </md></p>
</example>

<example>
  <title>An open cover of <m>[a,b]</m></title>
  <p workspace="2in">Let <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> be given.  For <m>x \in [a,b]</m> define <m>U_x = V_{\epsilon}(x)</m>.  Then <m>\mathcal{U}=\{U_x \, : \, x \in [a,b]\}</m> is an open cover of <m>[a,b]</m> because
    <md>
      <mrow>\displaystyle \bigcup_{x \in [a,b]} U_x \amp = \bigcup_{x \in [a,b]} V_{\epsilon}(x) = (a-\epsilon,b+\epsilon) \supset [a,b]</mrow>.
    </md></p>
</example>

</section>
  
<!-- ========================================   -->

<section>
<title>Heine-Borel</title>

<example>
  <title>An open cover of <m>[0,1]</m> with a finite subcover</title>
  <p>Consider <m>V_{1/2}(x)</m> and <m>\mathcal{U} = \{ V_{1/2}(x) \, : \, x \in [0,1]\}</m>.  This is an open cover of <m>[0,1]</m>.</p>
  <p workspace="1in">One finite subcover of <m>[0,1]</m> is
    <md>
      <mrow>\{V_{1/2}(1/4), V_{1/2}(1/2), V_{1/2}(3/4)\}</mrow>
    </md></p>
</example>

<theorem>
  <title>Heine-Borel</title>
  <statement>
    <p>A set <m>K \subset \mathbb{R}</m> is compact if and only if every open cover of <m>K</m> contains a finite subcover.</p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

<p>Note our textbook's Example 3.3.7.</p>

<proof>
  <p>
   (<m>\Rightarrow</m>) Suppose <m>K</m> is (sequentially) compact.  Let <m>\{U_i\}</m> be a countable open over of<m>K</m>.  We claim that there is an <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m> for which <m>\{U_i \, : \, i=1, 2, 3,\ldots,n\}</m> is a subcover of <m>K</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Suppose there is no such <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>.  Then <m>\{U_i \, : \, i=1, 2, 3,\ldots,n\}</m> is not a cover for any value of <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>.
  </p>
    <p>Because 
      <md>
        <mrow>U_1 \subseteq U_1 \cup U_2 \subseteq U_1 \cup U_2 \cup U_3 \subseteq \cdots \subseteq \bigcup_{i=1}^N U_i</mrow>
      </md>
      the successive unions of the open sets in the open cover form a nested sequence of open sets.  This means that
      <md>
        <mrow>K \setminus U_1 \supseteq K \setminus (U_1 \cup U_2) \supseteq K \setminus (U_1 \cup U_2 \cup U_3) \supseteq \cdots \supseteq K \setminus \large( \bigcup_{i=1}^N U_i \large). </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  <p>
    Since <m>\{U_i \, : \, i=1, 2, 3,\ldots,n\}</m> is not a cover for <m>K</m>, the set <m>K \setminus \bigcup_{i=1}^n U_i</m> is not empty.  Choose <m>x_n \in K \setminus  \bigcup_{i=1}^n U_i</m>.  Doing this for each <m>n \in\mathbb{N}</m> creates a sequence <m>(x_n) \subset K</m>.  
  </p>
  </proof>

  </section>
  
<!-- ========================================   -->

<section>

  <proof>
  <p>
    Because <m>K</m> is (sequentially) compact, <m>(x_n)</m> has a subsequence <m>(x_{n_k})</m> that converges in <m>K</m>.  Leet <m>x=\lim_k x_{n_k}</m>.  Since <m>K</m> is compact, <m>x \in K</m>.
  </p>
<p>
  Because <m>\{U_i\}</m> is a cover of <m>K</m>, <m>x \in U_m</m> for some <m>m \in \mathbb{N}</m>.
</p>
<p>
  Note that <m>x_m \in K/(\bigcup_{i=1}^m U_i)</m> so <m>x_m \notin U_m</m>.  Also, <m>x_{\ell} \notin U_{m}</m> when <m>\ell \geq m</m>.  This means that <m>(x_n)_{n=m}^{\infty}</m>, the tail of the sequence, is not in <m>U_m</m>.
</p>
<p>
Since <m>U_m</m> is open, there in an <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> for which <m>V_{\epsilon}(x) \subseteq U_m</m>.  Since   <m>(x_{n_k}) ]rightarrow x</m>, there is an <m>N \in \mathbb{N}</m> for which <m>k &gt; N</m> implies that <m>|x_{n_k} - x| &lt; \epsilon</m>.  That is to say, if <m>k &gt; N</m>, when <m>x_{n_k} \in V_{\epsilon}(x)</m>.
</p>
<p>
  But this is a contradiction.  So the claim holds.
</p>
  <p>
   (<m>\Leftarrow</m>) Suppose <m>K</m> has the property that every open cover of <m>K</m> has a finite subcover.  This is called the Heine-Borel property.  We want to show that <m>K</m> is sequentially compact.  We will do this by showing that <m>K</m> is closed and bounded.
  </p>
  <p>
    To show that <m>K</m> is bonded, consider the open sets
    <md>
      <mrow> V_1(x)\amp =\{y \in \mathbb{R}\, : \, |x-y| &lt; 1\} </mrow>.
    </md>
    These are the <m>1-</m>neighborhoods of <m>x</m>.  Then the collection <m>\{v_1(x)\}_{x \in K}</m> is an open cover of <m>K</m>.  Since <m>K</m> has the Heine-Borel property, this open cover has a finite subcover <m>\{V_1(x_k)\}_{k=1}^n</m>, noting that <m>x_k \in K</m> for all <m>k</m>.
  </p>
    </proof>

    </section>
  
<!-- ========================================   -->

<section>
  <proof>

  <p>
    Without loss of generality, we can assume that <m>x_i &lt; x_{i+1}</m> for <m>1=1,2,3,\ldots,N-1</m>.  Then
    <md>
      <mrow> x_1 -1 \amp &lt; x &lt; x_n+1 </mrow>
    </md>
    so <m>K</m> is bounded by <m>\max\{|x_1-1|,x_{n}+1|\}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    To show that <m>K</m> is closed we argue indirectly.  Suppose <m>(y_k) \subset K</m> is a Cauchy sequence with limit <m>y</m>.  This means that <m>y</m> is a limit point of <m>K</m>.  We need to show <m>y \in K</m>.
  </p>
  <p workspace="2in">
    Suppose not.  Suppose <m>y \notin K</m>.  Then <m>|x-y| &gt; 0</m> for all <m>x \in K</m>.  (The inequality equals zero precisely when <m>x=y</m>.). Define
    <md>
      <mrow>\mathcal{O}_x \amp =\{u \in K \, : \, |u-x| &lt; \frac{1}{2}|x-y|\}</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>
  <p>The closer <m>x</m> is to <m>y</m>, the smaller the radius of <m>\mathcal{O}_x</m>.  The collection <m>\{\mathcal{O}_x\}_{x \in K}</m> is an open cover of <m>K</m>.  By the Heine-Borel property, this open cover has a finite subcover, <m>\{\mathcal{O}_{x_i}\}_{i=1}^{n}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Consider <m>\epsilon_0 = \min\{\frac{1}{2}|x_i-y|\}</m>, which is the smallest radius of the open sets in our finite subcover.  Since <m>(y_n) \rightarrow y</m>, there is an <m>N &gt; 0</m> such that <m>|y-n-y| &lt; \epsilon_0</m> for <m>n &gt; N</m>.  But these <m>y_n</m> are outside every <m>\mathcal{O}_{x_i}</m>.  So out purported finite subcover does not cover <m>K</m>!  This is a contradicion.
  </p>
  <p>
    Consequently, <m>K</m> is compact.
  </p>
  </proof>


</section>



